Aron welcomes long time friend and mule deer slayer Marlon Holden to the podcast.  Marlon goes by @graylighthunter on instagram, and if you dont follow him, you have undoubtedly stumbled upon some of photos of the big deer he’s killed over the years.  Marlon is an incredibly talented photographer, and certified mule deer addict.  They drive into how Marlon got into hunting, why mule deer is his animal of choice, and his brand new app he developed, the GRAYLIGHT app.  A year and half in development, the Graylight App focuses on skillset building, continued education, bowhunting intuition, advanced proficiency, emotional intelligence, and mule deer IQ, all in a convenient and cutting edge digital platform.  From glassing, scouting, mountain safety, and field judging are just some of the many offerings from the GRAYLIGHT App.  Between Aron and Marlon there is an incredible wealth of knowledge that you won’t want to miss out on!

Passion and relentless pursuit, drive and desire, a positive mindset and mental framing… With these things, all things are possible… Here I am at 44 yards taking video of a bedded buck facing me… About 50 minutes later I arrowed him when he stood ~ #bigbucks #muledeer #graylighthunter #bowhunting #burrodeer #desertbucks #graylighthunter #bowhunter #graylightapp #fyp

Here’s a first look at the buck from the last video. With the rut just starting to hit peak, the old boys began to start settling in with the does! I spotted this guy from just shy of two miles away and the only look I got was a literal two second glimpse as he passed through a small window in the palo verdes lining an adjacent wash. After about 30 minutes of burning a hole in that spot, I found no further movement and opted to get off my high spot and move country to attempt to relocate him. After an hour of repositioning, I found him and his does bedded up on the off side of the wash in a thicket. After coming up with a plan I worked into 44 yards and found him bedded facing me but sleeping. So I decided to have a little fun and video him for you guys! Shortly after, he caught me move my bow arm a touch and I had to freeze for around 40 minutes. With numb feet and cramping arms, he finally turned his attention to his hot doe and stood up! I immediately came to full draw but he backed up and went behind the palo verde you see in the previous video and stood there. After a short while, he turned and fed out at 50 and I arrowed him quartering away, double lunging him! He ran all out for about 250 yards and piled up! After grinding hard for nearly two weeks, finding other shooters and not being able to hunt them, then finding this guy was just incredible! There were many highs and lows, lots of country covered and plenty of opportunities to arrow good bucks, however I just wanted something special. When their noses look short and their bodies make their antlers look small, you know you’ve got a big, mature animal in your glass! I guessed him to be low 80’s but he’s definitely much better after walking up on him! Incredible mass, extra deep tines and a huge body hid a lot! I never think to myself, “what if I wasn’t an outdoorsman”. I don’t often stop to wonder what it would be like to ignore the mountains and wild places of the earth. Then I look around me at all of those who have forgotten and I do think about the mountains, who I am and why I am who I am because of them… It is these times that I think, reflect and appreciate who and what I’ve become. Connected. In touch with reality and in love with our human process. If being a man means I need to hang up the bow, get rid of my equipment and sit in front of a computer, staring blindly at it in a cubicle all while being told that I am worth the value of the numbers on a direct deposit for my life essence, then I am not what “they” would call a man. I will continue to live with intention, not blinded by others agendas, no ego, just free to choose. This is only one of the ways that I believe men are intended to live. Defend those you love, protect those who need protection, love our God, work hard every single day take care of yourself and do so with an open, loving heart. #outdoorsman #graylighthunter #skregear #hoytbowhunting #provider #woodsman #woodswise

There comes a time when we must reconcile for our actions and connect with what it is that we are as human beings and who we are as individuals and look to origin. While this is part of the circle of life, there are many who are far removed from the connection that makes them a part of the eternal circle of life that is the very ethos of who and what we are… The arrow propelled from my bow, striking a merciful end to a life is much more graceful and deliberate that the reality of what each of these animals is predestined for as written by the fate of Mother Nature. For those of us whom share in the bowhunting community, we understand and realize this connection and for those whom do not partake, it can appear as selfish, cruel and unnecessary. Little do those who do not know, fully understand that no animal will die peacefully, naturally. For in the wild, an ungulates teeth will wear down after a maximum of 10-11 years and eventually will starve to death or succumb to starvation as a result of ground down molars. Those that die younger will fall to predation or bad winters where snow will force them to areas where the snow depth will not allow access to feed and as a result, starvation will follow. As a matter of fact, there is not a single ungulate that will be given a death where it can live a full life and die in peace, that is a mythical dream implanted by storybook fable alone. As a man, I choose connection to my food and pursue a quick, merciful passage. I appreciate this bucks life and honor him on my table until the time has passed, where I too will pass and the cycle is complete. We should all seek understanding and connectedness, as we are all in this together and the reality of death is the very gift of life! Might you not squander it and might you find that very beauty within yourself and others as a result of it. Seek that understanding and connection, let go of polarities and set yourself free from the idealism of justification to others and find resonance within yourself ~ #provider #muledeer #freerange #organic #graylighthunter #bowhunter #hoytbowhunting #cycleoflife

After grinding hard for ten days and passing on multiple bucks I was in search of a deer that simply became a ghost on me! A solid week of looking high and low left me without a trace of him to be seen. After two days of solid snow and 16” of fresh on top, I knew that the crunchy mess would ensue shortly. I had watched this pretty 4.5 year old rutting all week, he was number two on my hit list and I knew this was the perfect opportunity to wrap up an awesome hunt! I stalked in the fresh powder to 60 yards and had him facing me in his bed. One well placed arrow anchored him however he stood there at 68 yards and I sent one more to insure there was a quick passing. I have a love hate relationship with snow. This hunt is one that is near to my heart. There is something about the desert in January that has made its way in to my very ethos as an outdoorsman. I’m not sure if it is the weather, the habitat, rutting Muleys or the beginning of a beautiful new year of life we lead here on earth. With that said, as much as I desire to arrow a buck, I am careful not to shoot a buck simply just to tag out! I love to take my time and really immerse myself in the country and enjoy each day here. After scouting a lot pre season and knowing where to be on the opener, I hunted hard for this buck. Initially he was bedded out in a cholla flat with his does, however that soon changed when she got up and he followed him into a thicket of palo verde. I snuck in as close as I could and without much warning, she jumped out of her bed and bounded away! The buck got up and looked her way just as I ranged him at 68 yards. I drew on him right when he swung to look my way, however my pin was already settled on the small opening that revealed his vitals to the arrow already in flight! He mule kicked hard at the report of the hit and dove off the small knob as he rolled into the wash! I absolutely couldn’t have done this without my family with me and my boy @wild.in.the.hills We make a lethal team!
